1. Dataset Introduction¶

The csv contained in the zip file contains the results of a chemical analysis of 178 wine samples grown in the same region in Italy but derived from three different cultivars. The analysis determined the quantities of 13 constituents (ie. attributes) found in each of the three types of wines. This dataset has pre-assigned class labels, which represent the three wine cultivars. See this link for more information. https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Wine

2. Dataset Research¶

2.1 Motivation¶

Using this wine dataset, [1] visualized the clustering and predicted the classes, and found out that k-means clustering algorithm performs better than other clustering techniques such as PCA, LDA, SVM, etc. On the other hand, [2] tried to group similar observations together and determine the number of possible clusters since it may differ from 3, which would help the researcher make predictions and reduce dimensionality. For a more advanced technique, [3] introduced a new semi-supervised clustering algorithm that integrates both constraint-based methods and distance-function learning methods in a uniform framework, in order to produce better clusters than previously proposed clustering algorithms. The references are listed below.

References:

[1] Nath, Ayantika, and Shikha Nema. Clustering Visualization and Class Prediction Using Flask of Benchmark Dataset for Unsupervised Techniques in Machine Learning. International Journal of Innovative Technology and Exploring Engineering Regular Issue, vol. 9, no. 7, 2020, pp. 12971302., doi:10.35940/ijitee.g5943.059720. (http://www.ijitee.org/wp-content/uploads/papers/v9i7/G5943059720.pdf)

[2] Jankovic, Dina. K-Means Clustering of Wine Data. Medium, Towards Data Science, 13 Aug. 2018, towardsdatascience.com/k-means-clustering-of-wine-data-95bac074baae. (https://towardsdatascience.com/k-means-clustering-of-wine-data-95bac074baae)

[3] Bilenko, Mikhail, et al. Integrating Constraints and Metric Learning in Semi-Supervised Clustering. Twenty-First International Conference on Machine Learning - ICML '04, 2004, doi:10.1145/1015330.1015360. (https://www.cs.utexas.edu/~ml/papers/semi-icml-04.pdf)

Based on our literature research, we decided to use different types of clustering algorithm to grouup similar observations together, and to compare our clustering results with the ground truth.

2.2 Dataset Information¶

These data are the results of a chemical analysis of wines grown in the same region in Italy but derived from three different cultivars. The analysis determined the quantities of 13 constituents found in each of the three types of wines.

5. Pre-Analysis Questions¶

5.1 Is the dataset clusterable?¶

5.1.1 Hopkins statistic¶

In [16]:
n=len(wine)
num_trials=5
hopkins_stats=[]
for i in range(0,num_trials):
    n = len(X_scaled)
    p = int(0.1 * n)
    hopkins_stats.append(hopkins(X_scaled,p))
print(hopkins_stats)

[0.2963904703238161, 0.270161200656328, 0.28740010581460107, 0.25692769326087883, 0.25349243032072905]

Since the hokpins statistic is nondeterministic, we run it five times and the results are very similar. The hopkins statistic is around 0.28 which is not that close to 0, indicating that the dataset is clusterable but not shows a high cluster tendency. However, the hopkin's statistic is not a foolproof method for different datasets. Thus, we will try to corroborate our clusterability assessments with multiple analyses such as the t-SNE plot.

According to the t-SNE plot using the scaled dataset with perplexity = 30, we could get several findings:

1) The t-SNE plot shows that there are roughly three clusters in our dataset.

2) Each cluster has spherical shape.

3) Clusters have almost the same size and well separated.

4) There are some points between two clusters, indicating that there are some overlaps between clusters.

6. Algorithm Selection Motivation¶

  • From the background research, we know that k-means performs well in this dataset.
  • From the preliminary EDA, we found out that no two variables are strongly correlated with each other.
  • From the t-sne plots in the pre-analysis section, we know there are three underlying clusters which have roughly spherical shapes, similar sizes and are decently separated. In addition, all features are numerical.

All of these information also support us to use K-means.

One thing worth mentioning is that, there is no significant outliers in this dataset, so we do not consider using density-based clustering, because we do not want the algorithm to filter out the noise for us.

Other than K-means, we are also trying agglomerative hierarchical clustering, a "bottom-up" approach: each observation starts in its own cluster, and pairs of clusters are merged as one moves up the hierarchy. At the beginning of the process, each element is in a cluster of its own. The clusters are then sequentially combined into larger clusters until all elements end up being in the same cluster. The method is also known as farthest neighbour clustering. The result of the clustering can be visualized as a dendrogram, which shows the sequence of cluster fusion and the distance at which each fusion took place.

Last but not least, we are also performing fuzzy c-means clustering, just to compensate the fact that our first two algorithms are both hard assignments. Fuzzy c-means will provide us membership scores which reflects the assignment uncertainty in a straightforward way, so adding this algorithm in would make our analysis more flexible.

7. Clustering Algorithms¶

7.1 K-Means¶

7.1.1 Parameter Setting¶

For the K-Means algorithm, we need to determine the number of clusters (K) for our dataset. To select the optimal K, we use the metric of inertia with elbow method.

In [20]:
# use average inertia for selecting the best K (elbow method)
cluster_num_list=range(1,10)
avg_inertia_list=[]
for k in cluster_num_list:
    sub_inertia_list=[]
    for rs in [1001,1002,1003]: # use three random states
        kmeans=KMeans(n_clusters=k,random_state=rs).fit(X_scaled)
        sub_inertia_list.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    avg_inertia_list.append(np.average(sub_inertia_list)) # use the mean of the three trails
In [21]:
# plot the avg inertia wrt K
plt.plot(cluster_num_list,avg_inertia_list)
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters Requested in K-means')
plt.ylabel('Average Inertia of the K-Means Results (3 trials)')
plt.title('Elbow Method Results for Seeds Data')
plt.vlines(x=3, ymin=1000, ymax=2200, colors='red', ls=':', lw=1.5)
plt.show()

Interpretation:

As the number of clusters increases, the average inertia of K-means decreases. According to the principle of the elbow method, we prefer to the number of cluster that lies at the "elbow" which is the point after which the inertia start decreasing in a linear fashion. This elbow plot starts to level off at k=3 clusters. So the elbow plot is indicating that k-means will perform best with k=3 clusters.

The average silhouette_score for the K-Means is : 0.2848589191898987
In [26]:
# Compute the silhouette scores for each sample
sample_silhouette_values = silhouette_samples(X_scaled, wine['pred_clu_kmeans'])

n_clusters=len(wine['pred_clu_kmeans'].unique())


fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(1, 1)
fig.set_size_inches(18, 7)

# The 1st subplot is the silhouette plot
# The silhouette coefficient can range from -1, 1 but in this example all
# lie within [-0.1, 1]
ax1.set_xlim([-0.1, 1])
# The (n_clusters+1)*10 is for inserting blank space between silhouette
# plots of individual clusters, to demarcate them clearly.
ax1.set_ylim([0, len(X) + (n_clusters + 1) * 10])


y_lower = 10
for i in range(n_clusters):
    # Aggregate the silhouette scores for samples belonging to
    # cluster i, and sort them
    ith_cluster_silhouette_values = \
        sample_silhouette_values[wine['pred_clu_kmeans'] == i]

    ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()

    size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]
    y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i

    color = cm.nipy_spectral(float(i) / n_clusters)
    ax1.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),
                      0, ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
                      facecolor=color, edgecolor=color, alpha=0.7)

    # Label the silhouette plots with their cluster numbers at the middle
    ax1.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))

    # Compute the new y_lower for next plot
    y_lower = y_upper + 10  # 10 for the 0 samples

ax1.set_title("The silhouette plot for the various clusters.")
ax1.set_xlabel("The silhouette coefficient values")
ax1.set_ylabel("Cluster label")

# The vertical line for average silhouette score of all the values
ax1.axvline(x=silhouette_avg_kmenas, color="red", linestyle="--")

ax1.set_yticks([])  # Clear the yaxis labels / ticks
ax1.set_xticks([-0.1, 0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1])


plt.show()

The closer this score is to 1, the more cohesive and separated these clustering is. So an average silhouette score of 0.28 is somewhat low. So even though the t-SNE plot shows that the class labels are almost correctly predicted, the underlying cohesion and separation of this dataset is not strong, in which there are some connections among different kinds of wines.

7.1.3.3 Supervised Learning Evaluation¶

In [29]:
# Adjusted Rand Score
adjusted_rand_score(wine['pred_clu_kmeans'],wine['Wine Class'])
Out[29]:
0.8974949815093207

The Rand Index computes a similarity measure between two clusterings by considering all pairs of samples and counting pairs that are assigned in the same or different clusters in the predicted and true clusterings. The adjusted rand score for the pre-assigned wine class labels and the k-means clustering labels is pretty high.

In [30]:
# Homogeneity Score
homogeneity_score(wine['Wine Class'],wine['pred_clu_kmeans'])
Out[30]:
0.8788432003662366

Homogeneity metric of a cluster labeling given a ground truth. A clustering result satisfies homogeneity if all of its clusters contain only data points which are members of a single class. The homogeneity score for the pre-assigned wine class labels and the k-means clustering labels is pretty high.

In [31]:
# Completeness Score
completeness_score(wine['Wine Class'],wine['pred_clu_kmeans'])
Out[31]:
0.8729636016078731

Completeness metric of a cluster labeling given a ground truth. A clustering result satisfies completeness if all the data points that are members of a given class are elements of the same cluster. The completeness score for the pre-assigned wine class labels and the k-means clustering labels is pretty high.

df_metrics = df_metrics.append(pd.Series(['Kmeans','Adjusted_rand_score',adjusted_rand_score(wine['pred_clu_kmeans'],wine['Wine Class'])]), ignore_index=True)
df_metrics = df_metrics.append(pd.Series(['Kmeans','Homogeneity_score',homogeneity_score(wine['Wine Class'],wine['pred_clu_kmeans'])]), ignore_index=True)
df_metrics = df_metrics.append(pd.Series(['Kmeans','completeness_score',completeness_score(wine['pred_clu_kmeans'],wine['Wine Class'])]), ignore_index=True)

7.2 Hierarchical Clustering¶

7.2.1 Parameter Setting¶

For hierarchical clustering algorithm, we do not need to specify the number of clusters in advance and the result is a dendrogram. However, for the purpose of this project, we need to compare the performance of different algorithms. From pre-analysis, we can see that 3 is a decent number of clusters, thus we will specify the number of clusters to 3. Also, there is an important parameter in hierarchical clustering algorithm which is the method for calculating the distance between the newly formed cluster. Some common methods contain single linkage, complete linkage, average linkage and Wards linkage. We first try all the methods and select the one that has the best performance and conduct post analysis on the best method.

It looks like the hierarchical clustering algorithm with Ward linkage identified the three clusters that we expected we would find given the t-sne plot.

The t-SNE plot colored by the predicted cluster labels shows that there is no strong cohesion and separation for the three clusters. Compared to cluster 0 and cluster 1, cluster 2 has less cohesion since we could see some points that are far from cluster 2 are very close to the other two clusters.

However, compared to the result of the K-Means algorithm, the hierarchical clustering result has less cohesion and separation since there are more points that are not well separated. Also, there are more samples that are wrongly classified.

# The 1st subplot is the silhouette plot
# The silhouette coefficient can range from -1, 1 but in this example all
# lie within [-0.1, 1]

# The (n_clusters+1)*10 is for inserting blank space between silhouette
# plots of individual clusters, to demarcate them clearly.

y_lower = 10
for i in range(n_clusters):
    # Aggregate the silhouette scores for samples belonging to
    # cluster i, and sort them
    ith_cluster_silhouette_values = \
        sample_silhouette_values[wine['pred_clu_hire_ward'] == i]

    ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()

    size_cluster_i = ith_cluster_silhouette_values.shape[0]
    y_upper = y_lower + size_cluster_i

    color = cm.nipy_spectral(float(i) / n_clusters)
    ax1.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper),
                      0, ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
                      facecolor=color, edgecolor=color, alpha=0.7)

    # Label the silhouette plots with their cluster numbers at the middle
    ax1.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * size_cluster_i, str(i))

    # Compute the new y_lower for next plot
    y_lower = y_upper + 10  # 10 for the 0 samples

ax1.set_title("The silhouette plot for the various clusters.")
ax1.set_xlabel("The silhouette coefficient values")
ax1.set_ylabel("Cluster label")

# The vertical line for average silhouette score of all the values
ax1.axvline(x=silhouette_avg_hire, color="red", linestyle="--")

ax1.set_yticks([])  # Clear the yaxis labels / ticks
ax1.set_xticks([-0.1, 0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, 1])


plt.show()

The closer this score is to 1, the more cohesive and separated these clustering is. So an average silhouette score of 0.27 is somewhat low. So even though the t-SNE plot shows that the class labels are almost correctly predicted, the underlying cohesion and separation of this dataset is not strong, in which there are some connections among different kinds of wines.

7.3 Fuzzy c-means (FCM)¶

7.3.1 Parameter Setting¶

  • From pre-analysis, we can see that 3 is a decent number of clusters, thus we will specify the number of clusters to 3.
  • For the fuzziness parameter p, we know that the more this parameter is closer to 1, the less fuzzy the clustering will be. On the contrary, the more this parameter is closer to infinity, the fuzzier the cluster will be. In this case, we tried different values for p and see what value will give us the most decent fuzziness, and plot 3 t-sne plots for each value of p along the way.

7.3.2 Results Presentation¶

In [52]:
X_array=np.array(X_scaled).T
# Number of clusters
K=3
for p in [1.1,1.2,1.3,1.5]:
    cntr, W, _, _, _, _, pc = cmeans(X_array, c=K, m=p, error=1e-6, maxiter=20000, seed=1000)
    for i in range(0,K):
        dff['Cluster %s Membership Score'%str(i)]=W[i,:]
        # Plot the projected (x,y) coordinates
        points = plt.scatter(dff["x"], dff["y"],
                 c=dff['Cluster %s Membership Score'%str(i)], s=30, cmap="BuGn")
        plt.colorbar(points)
        plt.title('p = %s Cluster %s Membership Score \n Normalized Dunns Partitioning Coefficient: %s'%(p,str(i),pc))
        plt.show()
    print('----------------------------------------')

----------------------------------------

----------------------------------------

----------------------------------------

----------------------------------------

Out of the four values of p that we tested here, when p=1.1, the partition is too hard; when p=1.5, the partition is too fuzzy; it looks like p=1.3 best captures the cluster assignment uncertainty of some of the objects that we can see reflected in the t-sne plots. The normalized Dunn's partitioning coefficient value for the fuzzy c-means clustering algorithm with p=1.3 was 0.8623. This value of 0.8623 is fairly close to 1, which reflects a reasonable assignment (not too fuzzy and not too hard).

8. Analysis Summary¶

8.1 Algorithm comparison summary¶

In [63]:
sns.barplot(x="Method", y="Value", hue="Metric", data=df_metrics);
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.);

Our research motivation is to use different types of clustering algorithm to grouup similar observations together, and to compare our clustering results with the ground truth. Based on the adjusted rand score, homogeneity score, and completeness score for all 3 types of clustering algorithm we have tried, kmeans clustering and fuzzy cmeans clustering are the better algorithms. Their only difference is that kmeans clustering gives us a hard assignment, while fuzzy cmeans clustering gives us a soft assignment (membership scores for each cluster). It seems that hierarchical clustering is not performing as well as the other two clustering algorithms.

8.2 Insights summary¶

  • If we were to perform hard assignment on Fuzzy C-Means, the result would be very similar to the K-Means clustering algorithm.

  • For hierarchical clustering, different linkages will lead to different performances. The linkage should be determined by the shape of our dataset (t-SNE) plot.

  • For any future new wine data, if we would like to know which cultivar this new wine comes from, we can utilize the K-means clustering results and calculate the distance between this new data and each of the three centroids. Then whichever class that has the shortest distance between its centriod and this new point should be the predicted class.
